## Migration: `EventProcessor` → .NET 8

### Key Problems in the Original Code

| Issue | Why it breaks on .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — removed in .NET 5+ |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Still exists but unreliable for `WaitOne()` wakeup; throws `ThreadInterruptedException` only in specific wait states |
| `ManualResetEvent` + manual `Queue` + `lock` | Works, but is a hand-rolled version of what `Channel<T>` or `BlockingCollection<T>` already provide |
| Race condition | Multiple `Enqueue` calls can signal `Set()` but `Reset()` + single `Dequeue()` loses items |

---

### Migrated Code (idiomatic .NET 8)

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private Task? _processingTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _processingTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        try
        {
            await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (ct.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Clean shutdown — expected
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Channel is closed.");
    }

    public async ValueTask StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _processingTask is null) return;

        _channel.Writer.Complete();              // signal no more items
        _cts.CancelAfter(timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)); // hard deadline

        await _processingTask;                   // wait for drain or cancel
        _cts.Dispose();
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
    }

    private void Handle(string item)
    {
        // your processing logic
    }
}
```

---

### What Changed and Why

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread` + `ManualResetEvent` | `Task.Run` + `Channel<T>` | No manual thread/signal management; Channel is thread-safe, backpressure-aware, and handles the queue+signal atomically |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationToken` | Cooperative cancellation — the only supported pattern in modern .NET |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `Channel.Writer.Complete()` | Gracefully drains remaining items then exits the `await foreach` loop |
| `lock` + `Queue<T>` | Eliminated | `Channel<T>` is internally lock-free (unbounded) or uses fine-grained locking |
| Lost-item race condition | Fixed | `ReadAllAsync` drains all available items, not just one per signal |

---

### Pitfalls to Watch For

1. **`Thread.Abort` → `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — This is the #1 migration blocker. Any call to `Abort()` will throw at runtime. Search your codebase: `grep -r "\.Abort()" --include="*.cs"`.

2. **Fire-and-forget `Task.Run`** — Always store the `Task` and `await` it during shutdown, or unobserved exceptions vanish silently.

3. **`Handle()` exceptions** — In the original code, an exception kills the thread silently. Add a `try/catch` inside the loop if `Handle` can throw and you want to keep processing.

4. **Bounded vs. Unbounded** — `CreateUnbounded` has no backpressure. If producers are faster than consumers, use `CreateBounded<string>(capacity)` and switch to `await _channel.Writer.WriteAsync(item)`.

5. **Synchronous callers** — If `StopAsync` must be called from sync code, use `_processingTask.Wait(timeout)` as a fallback, but prefer async all the way up.
